ce:section.ce:para:
To explore the difference in fluorescence properties between GQDs and af-GQDs, a detailed PL analysis was performed by recording the PL curves under different excitation wavelengths (Fig. 5
                        ). It can be seen that the prepared GQDs and af-GQDs both exhibited an excitation-independent PL behavior. When the excitation wavelengths were increased from 260 to 380 nm, the positions of the maximum emission peaks were invariant. It is known that wavelength-dependent is the basic feature of radiative recombination resulting from the quantum confinement effect, because different sizes will lead to different energy gap distributions and further result in shifts in the positions of emission peaks [25,26]. Hence, the emission peaks of GQDs did not shift with the increase in excitation wavelength, thus indicating that PL enhancement cannot be ascribed to the size change of GQDs. Such a characteristic may be related to the content of surface states formed during acid oxidation and the highly homogenous nature of af-GQDs [27–29]. GQDs and af-GQDs both had two major emission peaks: one at 450 nm and the other at 510 nm ascribed to the π-π* transition of sp2 domains and the n-π* transition of surface functional groups, respectively. The oxygen functional groups formed on the basal plane and edges of graphene crystallites during the acid oxidation process, such as hydroxyl (OH), epoxy (COC), carbonyl (CO), and carboxyl (COOH), make GQDs easily disperse in water. The relative intensity of emission peaks of GQDs and af-GQDs is presented in Fig. 5. It can be concluded that the emission peak of af-GQDs was more prominent at a longer wavelength, while the emission peak was suppressed at a shorter wavelength. Furthermore, the emission peak at a longer wavelength shifted from 510 to 520 nm after the amino-hydrothermal treatment, which corresponds to the brighter and deeper yellow fluorescence phenomenon observed in af-GQDs. It was found that that the emission wavelength of GQDs depends on the energy gap between the ground and excited states and that different intrinsic electronic structures of materials can result in diverse electronic transitions. The UV–vis absorption and PL excitation spectra of GQDs and af-GQDs are shown in Fig. 6
                        , which reveals a wide absorption in the ultraviolet range and a long tail extending into the visible region. The absorption peak at approximately 230 nm belongs to the π-π* transitions of the sp2-hybridized carbon core domains, and a typical broad absorption band at approximately 275 nm corresponds to the n-π* transitions of oxygen functional groups, whose electron lone pairs conjugate with aromatic π electrons. Differently, af-GQDs had stronger absorption in the 400–500 nm range; this means that they require lower energy to induce more electron transitions. The photostability testing showed that 86% of the PL intensity of af-GQDs was reserved after irradiation with a 300 W xenon lamp for 1 h. Good PL performance under visible light and high photostability make them highly suitable for bioimaging and optical sensing. The fluorescence QY of af-GQDs was calculated to be approximately 13.8% with quinine sulfate as the standard, and this value was much higher than that of GQDs (4.7%), as shown in Supporting Information Table S1. PL and UV–Vis results indicated that the amino-hydrothermal treatment affected the oxygen functional groups on the surface of GQDs, inhibited the nonradiative recombination process of electron-hole pairs, and facilitated radiative transition. The lower band gap energy in af-GQDs caused by the amino-hydrothermal treating enhanced the possibility of electron transition, thereby leading to the predominance of n-π* transition in PL behavior and increase in fluorescence QY.
